body:
@vertextao Thank you for trying it and apologies for the hassle. Yes, I can confirm it doesn't work and it's 
not working even in cases that I had previously got it to work (please see below). Please revert the `lsan` stuff,  and go back to your initial proposal (up to and including 7a8a286).

Technically we need `__lsan_register_root_region(&mu, sizeof(mu))` so that asan searches that memory region for live pointers but asan cannot detect any live pointers there.

More surprisingly, the following program is actually leaking an int (in `new int(1)`) but asan can't find it because it stores the pointer in the mmap region. Even with `__lsan_register_root_region`, asan isn't able to detect the leak. I will get to the bottom of this later. Let's don't get blocked on this.

```
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <sys/mman.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <sanitizer/lsan_interface.h>

void store_pointer(void* region, int* num) {
  memcpy(region, &num, sizeof(num));
}

int main(void) {
  size_t pagesize = getpagesize();
  void* region =
      mmap((void*)(pagesize * (1 << 13)), pagesize,
           PROT_READ | PROT_WRITE | PROT_EXEC, MAP_ANON | MAP_PRIVATE, 0, 0);
  if (region == MAP_FAILED) {
    perror("Could not mmap");
    return 1;
  }
  __lsan_register_root_region(region, pagesize);
  store_pointer(region, new int(1));
  return 0;
}
```
